 English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Walrod","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Walrath  , a surname of German origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Walrath","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Wallrath  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Hoorde - Lord of Walrod was born in 1285, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Hoord Of Walrod and Maisters, was 43 and his mother, Jocosa Young, was 44. He had at least 1 son with Eva Mortimer."},"et":{"1285–":"1285–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1287–Female":"1287–Surnud","1327–Male":"1327–Surnud","1325–1381":"1325–1381","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1241–Female":"1241–Surnud","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1241":"1241","1381":"1381","Walrod, England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ellesmere, Shropshire, England":"Ellesmere, Shropshire, England",", Shropshire, England, UK":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bridgnorth, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bridgnorth, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1285–":"1285–Kuollut","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1287–Female":"1287–Kuollut","1327–Male":"1327–Kuollut","1325–1381":"1325–1381","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1241–Female":"1241–Kuollut","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","about 1325":"noin 1325","1287":"1287","1330":"1330","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1241":"1241","1381":"1381","